Personal passive is occasionally used, e.g. minǝxʷ ti min-wǝ ton kʷäl töärǝ (go-INF so go-PASS.3SG that house trough) 'they go continously through that house'.
The present participle is A/S oriented, whereas the past participle can refer to A, S, and P (teem ’who has eaten/which is eaten’).
"The caritive suffix attached to the verb stem produces a verbal noun, the use of which resembles a participle, and which modifies the noun".
There is no marking for the possessor, but the possesee is marked with the possessive suffix.
Adpositions show syncretism, e.g. kʷäl ji-poål-t (house back-side-LOC) 'behind the house' is used to mark location and goal; cf. kʷäl ji-poål-nǝl (house back-side-ABL) 'from behind the house'.
There is no genitive case at all.
Th lative is used but called dative in this function (and with personal pronouns).

In the examples, the case is the same. The ending is either -l or -tǝl. The latter appears in the possessive declension.

In attributive clauses the modifier has no case/number marker.
Indefinite objects are in the nominative case, whereas definite objects are typically in the genitive case.

Transitive verbs can agree with the object in person and number. Verbs in the objective conjugation express a bounded action, whereas verbs in the subjective conjugation (with definite objects) express unbounded actions. Furthermore, a definite object can also be in the inessive (the verb is in the subjective conjugation in this case) and this construction also expresses an unbounded action.
The subject is in the dative in necessive constructions.
PST2 expresses past habituality.
In addition to expressing repeated events, PST2 can also express events that were continuing in the past.
The forms of present cover both present and future time.

Aspectual oppositions can be expressed with the objective vs. subjective conjugation. In the past tense, the negative marker takes person marking, and the two conjugation types are differentiated in the negative marker.
The infinitive-participle -ma can mark necessity. The subject has to be in the dative case in this construction.
The passive/reflexive marker v is used to express capability, possibility, passive voice (depending on a context).
There is no reflexive conjugation, there is only the passive/reflexive marker v, e.g. Mar'a-n' tomba-v-s' ked'-eze (Mary-GEN hurt-PASS-PST1.3SG hand-POSS.3SG) 'Mary's hand got hurt'.

However, verbs like 'feed' and 'give drink' can take two objects, one in the ablative and the other one in the nominative/genitive, e.g. mon andsa sonze sivel'd'e (1SG feed-1SG>3SG 3SG.GEN meat-ABL) 'I feed him/her meat'.
2PL and 3PL subject are syncretic in the objective conjugation.
Sonze kudo-zo mazij (3SG.GEN house-POSS.3SG beautiful) 'His/her house is beautiful'.

The copula in the present tense has future reference. In the past tense, it is possible to use the copula with predicate nominals, but predicate nominals can also be conjugated in the second past tense: Sonze kudo-zo mazij-el' (3SG.GEN house-POSS.3SG beautiful-PST2.3SG) 'His/her house was beautiful'.
In other persons the locative adverbial gets verbal endings: Mon kudo-s-an (1SG house-INE-1SG) 'I am at home'.

It is possible to use the same coordinating conjunction in all cases, though with nouns different types of coordinating is also possible: Pet'a-t-Mar'a-t (Pet'a-PL-Mar'a-PL) 'Pete and Mary' or Pet'a Mar'a marto (Pet'a Mar'a with) 'Pete with Mary'.
In existential sentences, the negation particle aras' is used. In other sentences, the negation particle a is used in the present tense and the negation verb ez' in the past tense.
In the present tense, negation is symmetric, e.g. kort-an : a kort-an (speak-PRS.1SG : NEG speak-PRS.1SG) 'I speak : I don't speak'.
Participle and gerund forms are negated with the negative construction apak + connegative, instead of other constructions used with finite verbs.
saj-t' umar' (take-IMP.2SG apple) 'Take an apple'.
This is, however, rare in Erzya.
Both the singular and the plural is possible with numerals bigger than 1.

The abessive can be used as a case-ending or in an adnominal function as an adjective. The latter function might be more frequent. Therefore, the abessive is not considered as a case-ending in most of the grammars.
The inessive -so/-se can also be used as instrumental, e.g. salmuks-so (needle-INS) 'by/with a needle'.

The comitative suffix -n'ek is used very restrictedly and does not have all the features as other case ending have in the Erzya language. This ending is not considered as a case in most of the grammars and Salo (2016) argues that words with the -n'ek ending could even belong to a separate word class. Ves't' jalga-n'ek min' mol'-in'ek kino-v (once friend-COM 1PL go-PST1.1PL cinema-LAT) 'Once we friends went to the cinema theatre'.
The dative is used (see UT082).
Erzya has three declension types: basic declension, definite declension (expresses that the referent of the noun is known to the speaker and the listener) and the possessive declension.
However, there are also syncretic forms: singular and plural possession overlap in most cases.
The 3SG possessive suffix can be used instead of the definite declension with some unique nouns, however, this use is restricted.

The pronoun kije 'who' is not used, kona 'who, that, which' is used instead. It appears with animates: loman'-es'/buka-s', kona sa-s' t'eze (person-DEF.NOM/ox-DEF.NOM that come-PST1.3SG here) 'The person/ox that came here' as well as with inanimates t'el'e-s', kona juta-s' (winter-DEF.NOM which pass-PST1.3SG) 'the winter that is over'.
See the comment in UT107.
The possessive suffixes usually follow case suffixes: ked'-eze-nze (hand-ILL-POSS.3SG) 'into his/her hand'. In some cases, however, case suffixes and possessive suffixes are fused together.

Plural marking is used in the basic declension only in the nominative. In other cases the singular and the plural is distinguished only in the definite declension. The singular is unmarked, whereas in the plural the plural suffix t : t' follows the noun, and it is followed by the definiteness marker and the case ending.
леля; l'el'a 'uncle' is used for both.
There is only distinction for 'old', i.e. tašto 'old (inanimate), sir'e 'old (animate)'.

There is only distinction for 'cold': jakšamo 'cold' is used about (winter) weather, day (cf. also jakšamo-s' (cold-DEF) 'frost, cold weather), whereas kel'me 'cold' is used in a wide range of meanings, e.g. moda-s' kel'me (soil-DEF cold) 'the soil is cold', ked'-et' kel'me (hand-POSS.2SG cold) 'your hand is cold'.

The inherent length of vowels in a word, rather than stress affects the relationship between vowel lengths - stressed U may be shorter than unstressed a: nUla 'a piece of cloth'; intrinsically, the high vowels, u, i are shorter than the low a; the length of the stressed i, u may be equal to (or even longer than) that of the unstressed a.
No genuine geminates; at morpheme boundary, false geminates may be formed: van-n-oms (see-FRQ-INF).
Quantity has no phonological significance.

Mainly disyllabic trochaic feet are realized in speech, e.g. kUdo-sO-nzo (home-INE-POSS.3SG) 'in his/her home'. Trisyllabic feet, e.g. kUdo-so-st (home-INE-POSS.3PL) are also possible. Stress can move across word boundaries: c'Ora-t'-n'E ez'-t' tUje-vE kudO-v (man-PL-NOM.DEF NEG-PST1.3PL leave-PASS.CNG home-LAT) 'The men did/could not leave for home'. Stress is not distinctly expressed.
The variants of the emphatic particle (clitic) -jak/-kak/-gak 'even, too' (e.g. sOn-gAk 'he, too') tend to have primary or secondary stress.
The first syllable tends to be stressed if the word is uttered as a dictionary item; in words with more than two syllables, stressed and unstressed syllables alternate: mOdamAr' 'potato'.
Initial and non-initial stress alternate: mon E-z'in' mO-l'e /mOn e-z'In' mo-l'E (1SG.NOM NEG.PST-1SG go.CNG) 'I did not go'.
There are no diphthongs.
There are no diphthongs.

In South-Eastern dialects, e - ä: keď 'hand, arm' - käď 'leather, skin'; word-final e, i > ä: śimi > śimä 's/he drinks' .
They occur mainly in suffixes (as the result of elision).

raužo 'black', raśke 'ethnos, people', ruma-ms 'become bleached', Rav 'Volga', ruz 'Russian'

Enets postpositions usually convey local meanings but there are also some postpositions used to express temporal, comitative, causal etc. meanings.
One of the options is to express the subject of non-finite clause by an overt NP in oblique.
P is marked in the same way in finite and non-finite clauses.

However, only very few nouns distinguish between nominative and oblique in non-possessed forms, where properties of the object can be a decisive factor. For marking in the verb, topicality of the object is the most important factor.

In imperative clauses, the object is usually encoded with the nominative. However,  also accusative marking can be found, which could be Russian influence as such marking cannot be attested in the speech of previous generations.
"Irrespective of whether a clause is active or passive, its subject can be omitted if its referent is identical with that of the subject referent of the preceding clause."
Habitual is used to express a regular event.
This needs further research.
The aorist has no overt morpheme; the basic form of aorist refers to the past with perfective verbs.
The mirative interpretation is an extension of the perfect.
There might have been a desiderative mood once.

The subjunctive "expresses a hypothetical event with the basic tense-modal series, and an irrealis event with the past TM-series". Subjunctive is common in Forest Enets, very rare in modern Tundra Enets.
An analytic construction consisting of a conditional converb of the auxiliary with anterior participle is used.
Debitive is also used for the  expression of future.
The probabilitive is used to convey a probable event but also the interrogative "expresses a probable event in the past when combined with the contrastive tense-modal series".
The soft imperative is used to express mild commands.
It is not reflexive in meaning, but traditionally called so.
Plural or dual object in 2DU and 3DU are both marked by -ziʔ.
With the verbs of motion, the converb or supine is used, with other verbs the converb is used.
There are verbs which can never have an overt argument, and those which can be used with and without an overt argument.
Locative clauses are formed with copulas ɛ-/ŋa-.
Clausal negation involves a negative verb + a lexical verb in the non-finite connegative form.
There is a negative anterior participle (see also UT058).
Passive anterior participle (-duuj) relativizes objects, for all other participles there are frequency tendencies, not strict specializations.
All participles are unoriented, except passive anterior participle. (The perfective participle has two allomorphs: -iʔ and -miʔ).
Relativization of participants other than subject and object is very rare.
The respective participle is called negative anterior participle.
The posterior participle can be used to express future.
Both OV and VO are present; OV could be more frequent, but a separate study is needed.

Only an adverb, a personal pronoun in the accusative form, or a non-finite complement verb may stand between negative and lexical verbs, though this happens very rarely. All examples with accusative personal pronoun and a negative imperative verb show the O NEG V-CONN order in the corpus.

Morphological coincidence.
In the predicative position, the stative intransitive verb behaves like a verb.
However, there are postpositions that have never been attested with posessive suffixes.

does not combine with possessive suffixes and personal pronouns, and it does not have number forms.

The pronoun ʃee 'who' is also used for bear, but it is an exception. For all other non-human referents ɔbu 'what ' is used.

Relative clauses usually occur before the head noun in the NP.
The order becomes apparent from locative forms, and the order is fixed. Core cases (i.e. NOM and OBL) are always fused with possessive forms.
The oder becomes apparent from dual forms, whereas singular and plural possession is expressed cumulatively.
Enets has double or long vowels. However, cf. Helimski (1984), who analyses them as a sequence of two identical vowel phonemes.
Nonphonemic.

It could however be reasoned that postpositions that encode oblique arguments have been subject to morphologization and that it is only description tradition and orthographic norms that prevent them from being considered case suffixes (see EG 163-164).

“Possessive suffixes can be added to the long form of the gerund of prior action” (RHM 170). The same applies to the gerund of future action (RHM 172), participles (RHM 154-162); the picture is more complicated with postpositions (RHM 232) where the government depends on the individual postposition.
Differential object marking is only possible in non-finite clauses.

There is differential object marking only in non-finite clauses. e.g. кол кыч-аш
[kol kət͡ʃ-ɑʃ] (fish.NOM catch-INF) ‘to fish, to catch fish’, кол-ым кыч-аш [kol-əm kət͡ʃ-ɑʃ] (fish-ACC catch-INF)
‘to catch a fish’. The motivation for using nominative objects presumably lies on the intersection of definiteness and aspectuality.

Compound past tenses I & II (formed by present-tense form followed by ‘to be’ in the third person singular, either in simple past I or II) are habitual (the distinction between them is evidential). Also, aspectual auxiliaries (light verbs) илаш ‘to live’ and шогалаш ‘to stand up’ can be coupled with a converb and give the resulting pairing a habitual value.

Numerous defivational suffixes: -л [-l]: лӹмдӓш [lə̈mdɑʃ] ‘to name’ → лӹмдӹлӓш [lə̈mdə̈læʃ] ‘to call names’, -ешт [-eʃt]: колаш [kolɑʃ] ‘to hear’ → колышташ [koləʃtɑʃ] ‘to listen’, -кал [-kɑl]: айыраш [ɑjərɑʃ] ‘to separate’ → айыркалаш [ɑjərkɑlɑʃ] ‘to sort’,
-ед [-ed]: пуаш [puɑʃ] ‘to give’ → пуэдӓш [puedæʃ] ‘to hand out’. Also auxiliary опташ ‘to place (several items)’.
Aspectual auxiliary (light verb) ӹлӓш [ə̈læʃ] ‘to live’ is used.
Especially in combination with atelic verbs or verbal pairings, the verb тӹнгӓлӓш [tə̈ŋgælæʃ] ‘to begin’ is used as a future auxiliary.
Simple past tense 1 forms can, in a structure presumably borrowed from Russian, be used to denote something that is about to happen in the immediate future.

The usual way of expressing this is using the converb of prior action. Also simple past III & IV (distinction between them is evidential), formed by a simple past II form followed by a past-tense form (simple past I and II respectively) of the verb ‘to be’ in the third person singular, are “used to denote an action that preceded another action or is interrupted by it”.

The particle ылын [ələn] (‘to be’ in simple past II, 3SG) is placed after verbs in sentences “in reference to inferences, knowledge that was previously unknown, etc.” - including surprising events.
However, there is no grammatical disctinction between evidential and mirative forms: тӹдӹ шыжар-жы доно ӓрня нӓрӹ хынален кашт-еш ыл-ын [tə̈də̈ ʃəʒɑr-ʒə dono ærɲæ nærə̈ xənɑlen kɑʃt-eʃ əl-ən] (3SG little_sister-PX3SG with week about for_a_visit go-PRS.3SG) 'It turned out that s/he stayed at her/his sister’s for about a week'.

A conditional suffix -гецӹ [-get͡sə̈] can be found, but is marginal in usage: in modern language it is only used on the verb ‘to be’, ылгецӹ [əlget͡sə̈]; this form is used as a particle in combination with indicative forms.
There is a necessitive infinitive with the ending -мыла/-мӹлӓ [-məlɑ/-mə̈læ] and a future-necessitive participle in -шашлык/-шашлӹк [-ʃɑʃlək/-ʃæʃlək].
The future-necessitive participle in --шашлык/-шӓшлык [-ʃɑʃlək/-ʃæʃlək], which prototypically denotes necessity, can in some cases be used in this function. See also UT028.
Realized by a highly productive derivational suffix.

Probably Russian influence.

The element -ды-/-дӹ -[-də- ~ -tə- ~ -də̈- ~ -tə̈-] contained in numerous non-finite forms.

While the participle in -дымы is historically complex (negation element + ending of passive participle), it is treated as a unit in modern language.

The negation verb and the connegative form are tied to one another tightly. It is unusual for other elements (e.g., adverbs, pronouns) to occupy the space between them and it is unusual for the word order to change – the connegative form by default follows the negation verb.
There is no agreement, e.g. нӹнӹ пуры ыл-ыт [nə̈nə̈ purə əl-ət] (3PL kind be-PRS.3PL) ‘they are kind’.
Analytic formation is used: сек яжо (SPRL good) ‘the best’;сек < Russian всех.
The nominative case is used, e.g. карандаш [kɑrɑndɑʃ] ‘pencil’, кок карандаш [kok kɑrɑndɑʃ] ‘two pencils’.
One of the prototypical usage situations for the dative, which unlike the dative in Turkic or Ob-Ugric languages is not used in a spatial sense.
NB! The so-called comitative case mentioned in Mari grammars and textbooks has a radically different function.
“The comparative case is used in answer to the questions кӱлӓ [kylæ]? ‘like whom, as whom’ and мала? ‘like what, as what’”
The dative is used to mark benefactors.

It should be noted that inanimate nouns traditionally did not occur in the genitive at all; inanimate nouns serving as a modification do occur in the nominative, e.g. Вена университет [Venɑ universitet] (Vienna.NOM university) ‘University of Vienna’ (see mrj.wikipedia.org/wiki/%D0%92%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B0)

The possessive suffix is used to indicate a reference to something previously discussed or otherwise salient to the conversation. It is especially commonly used to refer to a subset of a larger whole that is salient.

“Both in Hill Mari and in Meadow Mari, the pronouns тидӹ [tidə̈] (тиде [tide]) ‘this’ and тӹдӹ [tə̈də̈] (тудо [tudo]) ‘that’ have short forms ти [ti] ~ тӹ [tə̈] (ты [tə] ~ ту [tu]). The long forms are used when they stand on their own and are subject to nominal inflection. Before a noun as an attribute, in Hill Mari only the short form is used, whereas in Meadow Mari either the short or long form can be used.”

The “degrees of freedom” depend on the case, e.g. эрг-ем-лӓн [erg-em-læn] house-PX1SG-DAT ~
эргӹ-лӓн-ем [ergə̈-læn-em] house-DAT-PX1SG
‘(to) my son’.

The same word is used in both occasions, e.g. шокшы игечӹ [ʃokʃo iget͡ʃə̈] ‘hot weather’ - шокшы вӹд [ʃokʃo və̈d] ‘hot water’; ӱштӹ игечӹ [yʃtə̈ iget͡ʃə̈] ‘cold weather’ - ӱштӹ вӹд [yʃtə̈ və̈d] ‘cold water’.

Geminate (long) consonants only occur at morpheme boundaries.

нӹллӹ [nə̈lːə̈] ‘forty’ (← нӹл [nə̈l] ‘four’ + лу [lu] ‘ten’)
Reduced vowels are shorter than full vowels, but there is a clear qualitative difference between non-reduced and reduced vowels, so it cannot be reasoned that vowel length alone is distinctive.
No distinctive vowel length at all.

In Hill Mari, some suffixes are stressed (usually the penultimate syllable is stressed in Hill Mari), e.g. the comparative suffix.

The penultimate syllable is generally stressed: ӓтямлӓн [æˈcæmlæn] ‘to my father’. However: ( 1 ) a number of suffixes are stressed in violation of these rules, ( 2 ) if the penultimate syllable has a reduced vowel and there is a full vowel preceding that syllable, the stress shifts to the previous syllable.
Syllable structure has no transparent effect on where stress falls.

The penultimate syllable is generally stressed. However: ( 1 ) a number of suffixes are stressed in violation of these rules, ( 2 ) if the penultimate syllable has a reduced vowel and there is a full vowel preceding that syllable, the stress shifts to the previous syllable.
Consistent palato-velar vowel harmony.
In Hill Mari, consistent palato-velar vowel harmony.
There are however two reduced vowels with similar values: ы [ə], ӹ [ə̈].
Very rare and the effect of a fairly recent loss of reduced vowels that did not happen in all varieties of Mari.
The palatal consonants [ʎ], [ɲ], [c] are frequently mislabelled as palatalized. Palatalized pronunciation under Russian influence and especially in Russian loan words does happen.
Only in Russian loan words among contemporary speakers.
However, phonemic status is debated.
Historically as allophones of the fricatives /β/, /ɣ/, /ð/ after homorganic nasals, i.e.: [mb], [ŋg], [nd]. Today /ɣ/ and /ð/ are widely pronounced as [g] and [d].

It is uncommon, but not excluded. There are some words of proto-Uralic origin that have an initial r. There are some varieties in which intial r is preceded by prothetic ə, however, presumably under Chuvash indluence.

Epistemic possibility can be encoded on the verb with the derivational suffix -hat/-het.

Diminutive marking is possible, but it is used only by some people when talking  to children, e.g. Mosikázd meg a kezecskéidet evés előtt (wash-DIM-IMP.2SG.OC PRV DEF hand-DIM-PL-POSS.2SG eating before) 'Wash your hands before eating'.
However, it is more common to use the postposition nélkül 'without'.

There is syncretism in the spoken Hungarian: both the illativ and inessiv case may sound -ba/-be, e.g. könyvtárba megyek 'I am going to the library', olvasok a könyvtárba(n) 'I am reading in the library', where -n does not sound.
There is a distinction between internal and external local cases, and there is also a third set used to express proximity.
ki 'who' is sometimes used for animals but such usage does not follow the standards. However, such usage is possible in dialects.
Usage of a demonstrative pronoun for human referent tends to have a pejorative meaning.
Length may also influence the quality.
It seems that secondary stressed derivational suffixes often contain a long vowel.
There are a lot of rising diphtongs in Hungarian dialects, e.g. Eastern and Palóc Hungarian vout be.PST.3SG 'szeip 'nice'.
There is ë in the major part of Hungarian dialect area, except North-Western subdialects, furthermore, there are rising diphtongs with ë, cf. Csángó and Old Palóc eën 'I'.

[ʎ] can only be found in the central-Palóc subdialects and Eastern subdialects, it is absent from the standard and the other dialects areas. Most of today's speakers cannot differentiate between [j] and [ʎ].
The finite verbs agrees with the nominal subject. Non-agreement is possible only between plural and dual in certain sentence types, like habitual and existential.

Adjectives in Inari Saami don't usually agree with the nouns, instead an attributive form is used with adjectives, e.g. puáris tááluin (old.ATTR house.PL.LOC) 'in old houses'. Pronouns and numerals agree in some cases fully and in some cases partially, e.g. tain tááluin (this.PL.LOC house.PL.LOC) 'in these houses', taan táálust (this.SG.GEN house.SG.LOC) 'in this house'. Finally, there are some adjectives that either are considered to follow the same rule as the pronouns and numerals, or as a variation have the attributive form.

The partial agreement cases in singular are the locative, illative, and abessive, in plural there is no agreement in comitative and abessive. With these cases the adnominal property word is in genitive form (in SG or PL).
It is possible to derive frequentative verbs from other verbs with various derivative markers.
There is no future tense in Inari Saami. The present tense can be used to mean something that will happen in the future.
Depending on the verb aspect, the structure 'is happening' can mean immediate future.
There is potential.

The IMP.1SG form is included in the Inari Saami dictionary (Sammallahti & Morottaja 1993) but there are no examples of the usage. It can be speculated to be used like this: Čáállum reeivâ (write-IMP.1SG letter-ACC) 'I should write a letter'.

There is also a caritive derivation for nouns and also for verbs, e.g.  viste > viste-ttem 'house - houseless', jäämmiđ > jämi-mettum 'to die - never dying'. There is also an abessive case, meaning 'without': viste : viste-ttáá 'house' : 'without house'.
luuhâm ja luhhum are the same form of a participle but from a different verb (luuhâđ 'to read' ja luhhuđ 'to be read').
Participle perfect can be used as action nominalization.
Participle present can be used as agent.

There are diminutive (perhaps not hypocoristic) verbal derivates, e.g. smakkiđ > smakkii-stiđ 'to taste - to taste a little'.
There is the same case for source and location (locative case).

If NP is in Nominative or Accusative case, the noun can have three different cases, 1 - Nominative, 2-6 - Genitive (accusative) or 7- ... - Partitive. If NP is in any other case, the noun can be inflected to any case and the number will partially agree with the noun.
The genitive suffix appears only in demonstrative pronouns. Otherwise the genitive forms differ only by stem changes.

Usually the order is case+px (tálu-st-is, house-LOC-POSS.3SG). There is an exception for abessive, where the order is px+case (e.g. táálusttáá, house-POSS.3SG-ABE). In comitative and abessive plural, the possessive suffix has divided the case suffix (e.g. tálu-id-ân-guin, house-COM-POSS.3SG-COM).

Dual is not marked on nominals (other than personal pronouns, reflexive pronouns and reciprocal pronouns). Dual is however marked on verbs, meaning that a subject in the plural may combine with a predicate in the dual.

However, that this does not apply to all dialects.

There is a conditional marker lulu- which is used with the infinitive (or perfect participle) of a verb (e.g. luluv låhkåt COND.1SG read.INF 'I would read'). However, this marker is probably best analyzed as a defective verb, and is hence not considered "morphological marking" here.
The conditional can be used in counterfactual conditional clauses (cf. however UT026).

In a NP in the nominative, a noun following a numeral higher than 1 is usually analyzed as being in the genitive singular. However, from a synchronic perspective, the genitive singular and nominative plural are syncretic, meaning that an analysis of bárne as boy.NOM.PL would be equally valid.

Standard Lule Saami reveals such distinction. In some varieties however, no age distinction is made.

There is a phonetic contrast between [æ] and [e], but there is no phonological opposition as they are in complementary distribution, e.g. [e] in germaj snake.NOM.SG vs. [æ] in gärmmaha snake.GEN.SG can be analysed as allophones of the same phoneme.
Cf. nuorra /nuorra/ 'young'.
Cf. manen /manien/ 'why'.

“On occasion, a grammatically singular noun that refers to a group of sorts (e.g., калык [kɑlək] ‘people’, кӱтӱ [kyty] ‘herd’, еш [jeʃ] ‘family’), or pair nouns/collective nouns [...], co-occur with plural forms of verbs. In these cases, singular verbal forms are however also possible, and recommended by prescriptive grammarians.”
There is no case agreement within noun phrases at all.
There is no case agreement within noun phrases at all.

It could however be reasoned that postpositions that encode oblique arguments have been subject to morphologization and that it is only description tradition and orthographic norms that prevent them from being considered case suffixed (EG 163-164).

“The gerunds in -мек(е) [-mek(e)] and -меш(ке) [-meʃ(ke)] take possessive suffixes; their agent, which can (but does not have to) differ from the agent of the superordinate (often finite) verb, can be marked by a preceding pronoun or noun. If the agent of the gerundial action is a noun, it can be in the nominative or the genitive. Inanimate nouns generally occur in the nominative, while animate nouns occur in either the nominative or genitive. When used with a genitive form, the gerund usually has a possessive suffix third person.” (EG 254) The same applies to participles (EG 261, 265, 266); the picture is more complicated with postpositions (EG 160) where the government depends on the individual postposition.
Differential object marking can be attested only in non-finite clauses (EG 70).

Compound past tenses I & II (formed by present-tense form followed by ‘to be’ in the third person singular, either in simple past I or II) are habitual (the distinction between them is evidential). Also, aspectual auxiliaries (light verbs) илаш ‘to live’ and шогалаш ‘to stand up’ can be coupled with a converb and give the resulting pairing a habitual value.

Numerous defivational suffixes, descending by their productivity: v-л [-l]: лӱмдаш [lymdɑʃ] ‘to name’ → лӱмдылаш [lymdəlɑʃ] ‘to call names’, -ешт [-eʃt]: колаш [kolɑʃ] ‘to hear’ → колышташ [koləʃtɑʃ] ‘to listen’, -кал [-kɑl]: ойыраш [ojərɑʃ] ‘to separate’ → ойыркалаш [ojərkɑlɑʃ] ‘to sort’, -ед [-ed]: пуаш [puɑʃ] ‘to give’ → пуэдаш [puedɑʃ] ‘to hand out’. Also auxiliary опташ ‘to place (several items)’.
Aspectual auxiliary (light verb) илаш [ilɑʃ] ‘to live’ is used.
Especially in combination with atelic verbs or verbal pairings, the verb тӱҥалаш [tyŋɑlɑʃ] ‘to begin’ is used as a future auxiliary.
Simple past tense 1 forms can, in a structure presumably borrowed from Russian, be used to denote something that is about to happen in the immediate future.

The usual way of expressing this is using the converb of prior action. Also simple past III & IV (distinction between them is evidential), formed by a simple past II form followed by a past-tense form (simple past I and II respectively) of the verb ‘to be’ in the third person singular, are “used to denote an action in the past that preceded another action, or was interrupted by it”.

The particle улмаш [ulmɑʃ] (‘to be’ in simple past II, 3SG) is placed after verbs in sentences in order to “to imply an uncertainty of sorts, or an inference, and in some cases also that an event was unexpected and surprising”, e.g. паша-ште лий-м-ем годым тудо мал-а улмаш [pɑʃɑ-ʃte lij-m-em godəm tudo mɑl-ɑ ulmɑʃ] (work-INE be(come)-PTCP.PASS-PX1SG when 3SG sleep-3SG be.PST2.3SG) 'While I was at work, it turned out s/he was sleeping'. However, there is no grammatical disctinction between evidential and mirative form.
Only periphrastic forms are used.
There is a necessitive infinitive with the ending -мыла/-мӹлӓ [-məlɑ/-mə̈læ], and the future-necessitive participle in -шашлык/-шӓшлык [-ʃɑʃlək/-ʃæʃlək].
The future-necessitive participle in -шаш [-ʃɑʃ], which prototypically denotes necessity, can in some cases be used in this function.

There is, however, a suffix -ан [-ɑn] that can be attached to participles (EG 253) to indicate that they denote possible states rather than real states, e.g. почмо [pot͡ɕmo] 'opened', почман [pot͡ɕmɑn] 'openable'.
Realized by a highly productive derivational suffix.
One of the prototypical usage situations for the dative, which unlike the dative in Turkic or Ob-Ugric languages is not used in a spatial sense.

The reflexive marker -алт [-ɑlt] can  be used to create impersonal clauses that lack actual impersonal/passive semantics but rather show that an action was carried out involuntarily (see EG 392). Morphologically the verb is then 3SG. Subject marking is not possible then.
Probably Russian influence.

Exclamative clauses and in sentences used to express a desire can have bare infinitive predicates (EG 255). In negation, the nominalization is used in negative existentical clauses to indicate emphatic negation (EG 379).
This typically happens in Mari (only) with causative verb forms. The verbs meaning ‘rain’, ‘snow’ , and ‘blow’ (wind) require a subject.
Copula is not needed, e.g. тудо пиалан [tudo piɑlɑn] (3SG happy) 's/he is happy'; it is, however, possible to use  one.
The element -ды- [-də- ~ -tə-] is contained in numerous non-finite forms.
Realized by a highly productive derivational suffix.
While the participle is historically complex (negation element + ending of passive participle), it is treated as a unit in modern language.

“The subject of a passive participle can also be indicated by a noun placed before the participle. As a tendency, inanimate nouns occur in the nominative, while animate nouns occur in the genitive, with the participle taking a matching possessive suffix.”
No agreement between modifiers and superordinate nouns in general; participles do not differ from this norm.
Works with all participles but the active participle.
The converb in -н, which overwhelmingly forms adverbial forms, forms a very small set of adjectives. This is not a productive process (EG 269).
The basic word order is SOV. There is no obvious deviation from the norm in the imperative, at least not on a regular basis.

“The negation verb and the connegative form are tied to one another tightly in Mari. It is unusual for other elements (e.g., adverbs, pronouns) to occupy the space between them and it is unusual for the word order to change – the connegative form by default follows the negation verb.”
“Non-finite verbal forms are not inflected for tense and mood, but maintain some verbal properties, for example the argument structure (i.e., they can still have objects)."

Adjectives do not agree with the noun in number in the predicateve position, e.g. нине сӱрет-влак сылне ул-ыт [nine syret-vlɑk səlne ul-ət] (these picture-PL beautiful be-PRS.3PL) 'these pictures are beautiful'.
Analytic formation is used.

“Genitive forms, especially of pronouns, can be used as nominals meaning ‘my one, mine’, ‘your one, yours’, ‘his/her own one, his/hers’, etc. In this case, they can be declined as nouns. Other suffixes, also case suffixes, can follow the genitive suffix.”
The morphologization of certain postpositions (e.g. дек ‘to’) is proceeding faster on demonstrative pronouns: туддек ‘to him/her’ (EG 136).
The nominative case is used on both occasions, e.g. пӧрт [pørt] 'house' кок пӧрт [kok pørt] 'two houses'.

The postposition деч [det͡ɕ] ‘from’ could be said to be a de-facto case for which the morphologization is complete; it is only description tradition and orthography that justifies its classification as a postposition rather than a case suffix (EG 163-164)

The three postpositions - деке [deke] ‘to’ (EG 169-170), дене [dene] ‘with’ (EG 170-172), деч [det͡ɕ] ‘from’ (EG 172-174) - used similar to external local cases in Finnic languages could be said to be de-facto cases for which the morphologization is complete; it is only description tradition and orthography that justifies its classification as a postposition rather than a case suffix (EG 163-164).

The postposition дене [dene] ‘with’ could be said to be a de-facto case for which the morphologization is complete; it is only description tradition and orthography that justifies its classification as a postposition rather than a case suffix (EG 163-164). NB! The so-called comitative case mentioned in Mari grammars and textbooks has a radically different function.

“The comparative case is used to express similarity, likeness and can usually be translated into English as ‘like something/someone’, ‘as something/someone’. The object/person with which a noun in the comparative is compared can be used in varying syntactic functions in the sentence: subject, object, etc.”.
The dative is used to mark benefactors.

It should be noted that inanimate nouns traditionally did not occur in the genitive at all; inanimate nouns serving as a modification do occur in the nominative (EG 61-68), e.g. Вена университет [Venɑ universitet] (Vienna.NOM university) University of Vienna’ (see www.mari-language.com).
“Like the possessive suffix third person singular […] this possessive suffix can beused as a determining element, though its usage is more typical of folklore texts” (OMJ 125).

The possessive suffix is used to indicate a rreference to something previously discussed or otherwise salient to the conversation. It is especially commonly used to refer to a subset of a larger whole that is salient.
The “degrees of freedom” depend on the case, e.g. пӧрт-ем-лан [pørt-em-lɑn] (house-PX1SG-DAT) 'to my house', пӧрт-лан-ем [pørt-lɑn-em] (house-DAT-PX1SG) 'to my house'.
There are no indications which would show that Cx before Nx is possible.

The same word is used in both cases, e.g. шокшо игечe [ʃokʃo iget͡ɕe] 'hot weather' - шокшо вӱд [ʃokʃo vyd] ‘hot water’; йӱштӧ игечe [jyʃtø iget͡ɕe] ‘cold weather’ - йӱштӧ вӱд [jyʃtø vyd] ‘cold water’.

Geminate (long) consonants only occur at morpheme boundaries. Minimal pairs are possible: ныллымше [nəlːəmʃe] ‘fortieth’ (← ныл [nəl] ‘four’ + лу [lu] ‘ten’ + ORD), нылымше [nələmʃe] ‘fourth’ (← ныл [nəl] ‘four’ + ORD).
Reduced vowels are shorter than full vowels, but there is a clear qualitative difference between non-reduced and reduced vowels, so it cannot be reasoned that vowel length alone is distinctive.
No distinctive vowel length at all.
No distinctive vowel length at all; geminate consonants only at morpheme boundaries.
However, as final unstressed [e] is reduced, it could be argued that the qualitative difference of this vowel is critical to the phonological disctinction between these words.
In Meadow Mari, suffixes containing full vowels are stressed, but this is in line with the regular stress rules.
The last full vowel (i.e. anything but [ə] or unstressed/reduced final [e], [o], [ø]) is stressed: пеледыш [peˈledəʃ] ‘flower’, пеледеш [peleˈdeʃ] ‘blossoms’.
Syllable structure has no transparent effect on where stress falls.
The last full vowel (i.e. anything but [ə] or unstressed/reduced final [e], [o], [ø]) is stressed.
Only for labial vowels.
Further palato-velar distinction for labial vowels.
There is however a “mid unrounded central vowel, reduced vowel similarly to the English reduced vowel that is denoted in different ways (alone, lemon, heaven)”, e.g. пыл [pəl] ‘cloud’.
Fairly rare and the effect of a fairly recent loss of reduced vowels that did not happen in all varieties of Mari.
The palatal consonants [ʎ] and [ɲ] are frequently mislabelled as palatalized. Palatalized pronunciation under Russian influence and especially in Russian loan words does happen.
Only in Russian loan words among contemporary speakers.
Only in Russian loan words.

Historically as allophones of the fricatives /β/, /γ/, /δ/ after homorganic nasals, i.e.: [mb], [ŋg], [nd]. “The historical pronunciation of these sounds is encountered only rarely today: [β] has generally been replaced by [v]; /b/ is perceived as an independent phoneme; the sounds [γ] and [δ] are mainly realized as [g] and [d] in all positions.”

It is uncommon, but not excluded. There are some words of proto-Uralic origin that have an initial r. There are some varieties in which intial r is preceded by prothetic ə, however, presumably under Chuvash indluence.

“Historically, Mari had three voiced fricative phonemes: /β/, /γ/ and /δ/ […] The historical pronunciation of these sounds is encountered only rarely today: […] the sounds [γ] and [δ] are mainly realized as [g] and [d] in all positions.”
Only in Russian loan words.

“Historically, Mari had three voiced fricative phonemes: /β/, /γ/ and /δ/ […] The historical pronunciation of these sounds is encountered only rarely today: […] the sounds [γ] and [δ] are mainly realized as [g] and [d] in all positions.”
“Historically, Mari had three voiced fricative phonemes: /β/, /γ/ and /δ/ […] The historical pronunciation of these sounds is encountered only rarely today: [β] has generally been replaced by [v]”.
Only in Russian loan words.

There is alternation between [t] and [d] (not marked in orthography; д is used regardless of pronunciation) that has been said to resembles consonant gradation or final consonant devoicing: кид [kit] ‘hand’, кит-лан [kit-lɑn] hand-PX1PL, кид-ем [kid-em] hand-PX1SG. However, the historical explanation here is that [d] was spirantized to [ð] between vowels, and was later replaced by [d] under Russian influence.
In attributive clauses the modifyer has no case/number marker.
The subject is in the dative in necessive constructions.
PST2 expresses habituality.
In addition to expressing repeated events, PST2 can also express events that were continuing in the past.
The forms of present cover both present and future time reference.

Aspectual oppositions can be expressed with the objective vs. subjective conjugation. In the past tense, the negative marker takes person marking, and the two conjugation types are differentiated in the negative marker.
The infinitive-participle -ma can mark necessity. The subject has to be in the dative case in this construction.
The passive/reflexive marker v is used to express capability, possibility, passive voice (depending on a context).
There is no reflexive conjugation, there is only the passive/reflexive marker v, e.g. käd'-ǝn-za tapa-v-s't' (hand-PL-POSS.3SG break-PASS-PST1.3PL) 'his/her hands got broken'

However, verbs like 'feed' and 'give drink' can take two objects, one in the ablative and the other one in the nominative/genitive, e.g. andǝ-maz' jam-da (feed-3PL>1SG porridge-ABL) 'They fed me with porridge'.
In Moksha, 2nd and 3rd person plural is always distinguished: kunda-samas't' (catch-PRS.2PL>1SG/1PL) 'you catch me/us' and kunda-samaz' (catch-PRS.3PL>1SG/1PL) 'they catch me/us'.
The copula is covert: son mokšа (3SG.NOM Moksha) 's/he is a Moksha'.

The copula in the present tense has future reference.  In the past tense, it is possible to use the copula with predicate nominals, but predicate nominals can also be conjugated in the second past tense: Mar'a stir'-ks mazije-l' (Mary girl-TRA beautiful-PST2.3SG) Mary was beautiful as a girl.
In other persons the locative adverbial gets verbal endings: Mon kud-s-an (1SG house-INE-1SG) 'I am at home'.

It is possible to use the same coordinating conjunction in all cases, though with nouns different types of coordinating is also possible: t'äd'ä-t-s't'iR'-t' (mother-PL.NOM-girl-PL.NOM) 'mothers and daughters'.

In existential sentences, the negation particle aš is used. In other sentences, the negation particle af is used in the present tense and the negation verb iz'- or aš- (which conjugates according to person) in the past tense.
In the present tense, negation is symmetric, e.g. koRt-an : af koRt-an (speak-PRS.1SG : NEG speak-PRS.1SG) 'I speak : I don't speak'.

Participle and gerund forms are negated with the negative construction apak + connegative (in Moksha the connegative with the participle apak ends in k, similar to the imperative of the 2nd person singular), instead of other constructions used with finite verbs.
See also UT055.
The past participle and the gerund are syncretic only in the negated forms. In affirmative forms, there are different endings for the past participle and the gerund.
saJ-t' mar' (take-IMP.2SG apple) 'Take an apple'.
It is possible to place an object between the negative marker and the main verb, but it is not very common.
It is possible to use either the nominative or the ablative with numerals.
Both the singular and the plural is possible with numerals bigger than 1.

The abessive can be used as a case-ending or in an adnominal function as an adjective. The latter function might be more frequent. Therefore, the abessive is not considered as a case-ending in most of the grammars.
The inessive -sa expresses the instrumental as well: mašina-sa (car-INE) 'with a car'.
The dative is used (see UT082).
Moksha has three declension types: basic declension, definite declension (expresses that the referent of the noun is known to the speaker and the listener) and the possessive declension.
The 3SG possessive suffix can be used instead of the definite declension with some unique nouns, however, this use is restricted.

The pronoun kijä 'who' is not used frequently, but the kona 'who, that, which' is used instead. It appears with animates: loman'-c'/buka-s', kona sa-s' c'ej (person-DEF.NOM/ox-DEF.NOM that come-PST1.3SG here) 'The person/ox that came here' as well as with inanimates valks-s', kona lis'-s' mel'ä (dictionary-DEF.NOM which come.out-PST1.3SG) 'the dictionary that came out last year'.
Kona 'who, that, which' is used with both animates and inanimates (see UT107).

The possessive suffixes follow the case suffixes, e.g. vel'ǝ-sǝ-n (village-INE-POSS.1SG) 'in my village', except for the genitive and dative, which precede the possessive suffixes ava-z'ǝ-n' (mother-POSS.1SG-GEN) 'my mother's', ava-z'ǝ-n'd'i (mother-POSS.1SG-DAT) 'for my mother'

Plural marking is used in the basic declension only in the nominative. In other cases, the singular and the plural is distinguished only in the definite declension. The singular is unmarked, whereas in the plural the plural suffix t : t' (sometimes just the voicelessness of the previous consonant) follows the noun, and it is followed by the definiteness marker and the case ending.
There is only distinction for 'old', i.e. tašta 'old (inanimate)', s'ir'ä 'old (animate)'.
There is only distinction for cold: kel'mä ved' 'cold water', ušǝ-sa jakšama (outside-INE cold) 'it is cold outdoors'.
See UT125.
The variants of the emphatic particle (clitic), -ga, -ge, -ka, -ke, -vok, -nga 'even, too': mon-ga 'me, too' tend to have primary or secondary stress.

The first syllable tends to be stressed if the word is uttered as a dictionary item; in speech, mostly disyllabic feet with a stressed and unstressed syllable alternate: MOn sǝrxk-An insAru. - Mon sƏrxk-an InsarU 'I will go to Insar'.

A tendency to stress the non-first syllable is noticeable in words with the high vowels i, u in the first syllable and the low vowels a, ä in a non-first syllable: śijÄ 'silver', kujA 'fat'. However, rhythmic initial-syllable stress functions in these words as well.
Before front vowels, labials and velars may be palatalized: ve 'night' > v'e, kev 'stone' > k'ev'.

There is an agreement with the logical subject. In the comitative construction the agreement is dual (plural), however a few instances of singular. the verb is always in dual if the subject in a pronoun in dual. If there are two grammatical subjects (such as my mother and my father) in a sentence, the predicate is in the dual. This expresses that the two subjects act together. After quantifiers such as ŋukəgəə ‘many, much’, bǝnsǝ ‘all’ or numerals, the predicate agrees formally with the subject, i.e. it appears in the singular.
The predicate agrees in person and number with the subject.
Verbs in the objective conjugation agree with the object in number, the ending depends on the number. The verbal marker for object in dual is complex, it contains the dual marker.
Yes, but only partially: Only the declination of three grammatical cases (nominative, accusative, genitive) can appear on adjectives. In all other cases, the pre-modifier is in the genitive case.
In all locative cases.
The subject of the temporal clause may be appear in the genitive.
With some imperative forms the nominative is used.
In the active sentence, the over subject is always expressed with the nominative case.
The suffix -mUNHA shows that a situation takes place reguraly.
However, the imperfective verbs in the aorist tense refer to the present tense and thus express progressivity.
The resultative is used to indicate that an action will start immediately.
All tense markers can appear on the negative auxiliary.
The dubitative mood may be used to express surprise. There is also an exclamative clitic that has a mirative usage.
Optative may be used to express wishes or admonition. This mood is, however, rarely attested.
There is necessitive (or debitive mood), but it is only seldom used.
There is a speculative mood that is used to express speaker's assumptions.
Reflexive-medial conjugation shows the same person/number marking, e.g. ďeŋhiďi-Ɂi-ti is used for 2DU and 3DU (< ďembiɁsʲi 'to dress').
Passive sentences are formed using a passive suffix or a passive participle.
The bare infinitive occurs with motion verbs.
Tense and mood markers only appear on verbal categories.
If the pivot is expressed by a pronoun, copula is not obligatory.
Conjunctive coordinated clauses are usually juxtaposed without any coordinator. However, there are also some borrowed coordinators. The Russian coordinator is only used at the clause level.
The abessive participle.
Passive structures can be formed from both transitive and intransitive verbs.
The abessive participle refers to actions that have not yet occurred.
However, Helimski (1998) treated the necessitative participle as a future participle.
Participles show only partial agreement in case.
However, there is a separate suffix to indicate professioals, e.g. basu-Ɂsʲi ‘professional hunter’.
The negative verb must precede the main verb, e.g. ŋanuďətə ŋəmsu ŋuəi-kalʲi-Ɂ ńi-Ɂ mətu-Ɂ [ordinary meat one-CAR-ADV NEGAUX-IMP.2SG cut-CNG] ‘Don’t cut an ordinary meat!’
However, there is a suffix that can be used in the attenuative meaning (i.e. to do sth a bit).
Analytic constructions are used.
Plural or dual is rarely used.
Historically, there was an endin (-ŋ).
The lative is also used to express the recipient and the beneficiary.
Prolative is used to mark direction.
The suffix has been recently developed from the lative postposition na.
In addition to a postpositional phrase also the similative marker can be used to express equality.
With paired body parts, dual is typically used. In modern texts also plural can be found.
The non-pronominal possessor appears in the genitive case, whereas the pronominal possessor occurs in the nominative case (see also UT102).
The nominative form is used with pronouns.
The possessive suffixes refer to the person and number of the possessor but also the number of the possessed.
The referential use of 2sg possessive suffix may occur only when the marked NP occurs in the subject position (see also UT105).
Possessive suffixes can be used in the referential function that is similar to the definite article but it cannot be argued that the language has definite articles.
The distinction is made between humans vs. non-humans. However, in certain cases, 'what' can also be used for a human referent.
There are no relative pronouns.
There are no relative pronouns.
In plural, the number marker and the case suffix are fused.
However, see Wagner-Nagy (2018: 73): "words that end in long vowels or in vowel sequences trigger stress".
It is possible but rare.
with limitations
with limitations
with limitations

Janhunen, Gruzdeva (2020): "Nganasan has bimoraic long vowels and vowel sequences, some of which are of a Proto-Samoyedic
origin, as well as two monomoraic “diphthongs”, which Wagner-Nagy renders as [͡ia] and [u͡a], but which could more properly be rendered by monosegmental symbols like [ä] and [å], respectively, especially as they are actually often pronounced as monophthongs"
/ia/, /ua/ could be also interpreted as monophthongs
Janhunen, Gruzdeva (2020): "there would be three unrounded back vowels /a ë ï/, three rounded back vowels /å o u/, three unrounded front vowels /ä e i/, and one lonely high rounded front vowel /ü/."
also defined as /ɨ/
also defined as /ǝ/
/å/ is also defined as /ua/
/ä/ is also defined as /ⁱa/

Janhunen, Gruzdeva (2020): "it is totally unnecessary to distinguish notationally the intervocalic spirant [ð] and the postnasal voiced stop [d], as they represent allophones of a single phoneme that could easily be rendered as /d/."
The adnominal property word agrees with the head noun in all cases.
The negation is formed using a negative particle.
Potential is not used very often.
Typically, the conditional mood is used.
It is common to use the copula, e.g. Mie ole-n pihalla (I be-1SG outside) 'I'm outside'.
The subject is encoded with the genitive.
There are separate action nominalizations, e.g. šynny-ntä (< šyntyö) 'birth', juo-mini (< juuvva) 'drinking'.
Additionally, pronouns appear in the accusative case.
Zaikov (2013), however, considers šuati as postposition.
The postposition myötiä 'along' is used instead.
The locative case shows syncretism with the lative case, e.g. štola-lla (table-ADE/ALL) 'to the table, on the table'.
There is syncretism between goal and location marking.
The comitative is added to the plural stem but it can either have a singular or plural interpretation, cf. venehe-llä (boat-ALL/ADE) 'by boat'.
A postposition is used instead, e.g. šilma varoin paiššetty (you.PRT for bake-PASS.PST.PTCP) 'baked for you'.
case suffix + possessive suffix
number + case suffix
ŋ is an allophone, e.g. kenkät [ˈkeŋ.kæt] 'shoes'
Cf. vasara, sakara (also in Tver) (see Zaikov 2013).
In recent loanwords only (e.g. balalaikka).
Finite verbs agree in number and person with the subject.
The verb not only indicates that the object is determinate but also encodes the number of the object (SG, PL, DU).
Attributive adjectives are not inflected for case or number.
There is no future tense in Mansi, the present tense may also get future interpretation in a proper context.
The respective meaning is usually conveyed by the verb in the present tense form + context.
Tense is marked on the lexical verb.

In Northern Mansi, mirative forms have evolved through desubordination, thus, there is reason to regard mirativity as a separate category. The category of evidentiality and, accordingly mirativity, has different origins in Khanty dialects.

For the 1st person the particle wos ~ os with indicative present may be used;However, -nuw, conventionally labelled as a conditional marker, is also used as an optative marker, e.g. jomas jurt wēk χōnt-nuw-əm (good friend only find-COND-1SG 'If only I found a good friend / I would want to find a good friend'.

The 'if'-clause does not contain conditional marker (see Riese 2001: 48), e.g. at ke jursʲ-al-as-lən manar-e al-nuw-uw (NEG if team_up-MOM-PST-SG<2SG what-SG<3SG kill-COND-1PL) ’If you wouldn't have taken me as a companion, what would have we hunted?’.
There is syncretism between 2SG ~ 2DU ~ 2PL possessive suffixes, e.g. śōpit-as-aγən repair-PST-DU<2SG ~ repair-PST-DU<2DU ~ repair-PST-DU<2PL.
Such instances are possible but only as a result of very modern Russian influence.
Possible Russian influence, but early.

There are no original coordination conjunctions in Mansi; NPs have their own coordinating strategies (e.g. dual or plural forms or the particle os 'also'); VPs and clauses are connected through juxtaposition or bridging linkage (based on non-finite clause combining). Recently the Russian i 'and' is borrowed - and the functions of os 'also' are extended to clauses.
There is a separate element for existential negation – āt'im.
The suffix -tāl ~ -tal is used to make privative adjectives from nouns and privative participles from verbs.
The past and present participles are not specialized, but there is a past passive participle relativizing direct  objects/patient only.
The past and present participles can relativize all core and some non-core participants.
The suffix -tāl ~ -tal is not transparent from a syncronous perspective.
However, the present participle is actually a non-past participle, referring both to the present and the future.
As North Mansi has no genitive, all subjects are in nominative.
Agentive nominalizations use lexical nominalizers like xum 'person' with a participle.

Same word order as in declarative clauses - OV - unless it appears in emphatic construction, esp. in newer Russian-influenced texts (due to the focus position in Russian being in the sentence-final position).

However, as Mansi "preverbs are separable; most of them are morphologically still transparent; and many of them still function as adverbs" it has been argued that they should be regarded as verbal particles.
As there is no genitive in Mansi, the nominative is used (i.e. zero marking) for both  possessors and subjects of non-finite forms; but personal marking is with possessive suffixes.
The nominative is the only option for nouns; for pronouns there are oblique forms (traditionally called accusative, though the classification is problematic).
There are, however, also adpositions which do not make such a distinction.

Oblique forms (traditionally called accusative, though the classification is problematic), e.g. ānəm 'me', 
tawe 'him/her'; originally they are pronouns with possessive  markers of the same person; they can take other case 
markers, e.g. ānəm-nəl (1SG.OBL-ABL) 'from me'.
The nominative case is used.
The numeral kit 'two' can be followed by singular or dual.

However, there is a suffix -tal ~ -tāl traditionally classified as a privative derivational suffix (when used denominally) and the negative participle when used deverbally. But!
Denominal forms can also be used as indirect objects, e.g. neː-taːl χos oːl-əs (woman-PRIV long live-PST.3SG)
'(he) lived without a wife for a long time' (OUDB > northern mansi > 1239: 4). Thus one could in theory call this a case suffix too.
The lative has two basic functions: 1) indirect object, 2) goal of a movement.
Additionally there is a comitative postposition used both with animate nouns and personal pronouns.
A postpositional construction is used.
The respective case (called the translative) has both functions.
Cf. sam-pal 'one eye' (lit. half an eye). With possessive marking the dual appears: sam-aγ-e 'his (two) eyes'.
The possessor is always unmarked.
The nominative case is used for the possessive attribute.
There are separate suffixes for singular, dual and plural possession.
Whether the possessive suffix indicates possession or definiteness, becomes clear from the context.
The distinction is humans vs. non-humans, χōηxa/χotjut 'who' is used with people and manər 'what' with animals or inanimate objects.
There are no relative pronouns, only in very modern texts as obvious Russian influence.
There are no relative pronouns, only in very modern texts as obvious Russian influence.
The sequence is: stem + possessive suffix + case suffix.
The order is number + case.
No contrastive length of consonants.
Mansi has consistent first syllable stress.
Stress depends on the position and not on the weight of the syllable.
On phonological level there are no reduced vs. full contrastive subsets. In non-first syllables there is a middle, central [ǝ] but this is not a reduced vowel.
Allophonic variant of front high unrounded [I].
Present in Russian loanwords.
In three-constituent consonant clusters, the first constituent is the coda of the previous, the second and third consonants are the onset of the next syllable, cf. Coda-maximalization.
Only in monosyllabic words and in word-final syllables.

Three (or more) constituent clusters in stems are sporadic; they occur mostly in derivations or other affixed forms on morpheme boundaries. (In most cases a non-phonemic epenthetic schwa appears before the third or fourth constituent of non-homorganic clusters: njeːlǝm ‘tongue’ ⟶ njeːlm-ǝt tongue-pl, joxt-ǝs come-pst(.3sg) ⟶ joxt-sǝm come-pst.1sg.)
There are no palatalized, but alveo-palatal consonants.
No palatalized, but alveo-palatal consonants.
Present in Russian loanwords.
More precisely an alveo-palatal consonant.
More precisely an alveo-palatal consonant.
There are no affricates in North Mansi.
There are no affricates in North Mansi.
Present in Russian loanwords.
Present in Russian loanwords.
There is contrast between /k/ vs. /kʷ/, /χ/ vs. /χʷ/.
Phonotactic constraint: [ɣ] does not occur in word initial position.
Present in Russian loanwords.
No gradations but paradigmatic alternations.
No gradations but paradigmatic alternations.

The only adjective that agrees with the noun in case (and number) is buorre 'good', but it does not fully agree in all cases. E.g., buorre ovdamearka (good.NOM example.NOM), buori ovdamearkka (good.GENACC example.GENACC), buriin ovdamearkkain (good.COM example.COM), but buori ovdamearkkas (good.GENACC example.LOC). Additionally, many if not most present-day speakers (and even language authorities) use the non-declined buorre (NOM) in all cases.
There are cases that do not show full agreement, but have genitive modifiers instead.
There are many derivational suffixes with frequentative meaning.
The adverb aiddo 'just' makes the prxoimative function of the progressive (”action essive”) form even more explicit.
The so-called potential mood is somewhat different from its namesake in Finnish, but sometimes fits into this category.

However, in some Torne dialects, causative verbs take two objects: Niillas daga-h-ii rávdi niibbi (Niillas make-CAUS-PST.3SG smith.GENACC knife.GENACC). Cf. other dialects: Niillas daga-h-ii rávdái niibbi (Niillas make-CAUS-PST.3SG smith.ILL knife.GENACC) ’Niillas made the smith make him a knife.’
Used colloquially, probably increasingly used due to Scandinavian influence.

The agentive participle is homonymous with the action nominalization except for three-syllable stems, but even then, the agentive participle is identical with the short variant of the action nominalization used in compounds: čállin 1) write + agentive participle (’written by’)  or 2) action nominalization ’(act of) writing’); jorgalan translate-AG.PTCP >< jorgaleapmi translate-AN, but jorgalan- in, e.g., jorgal-an-bargu translate-AN-work

The contrastive length of vowels is present in the Western Inland dialects and in the Eastern Inland dialects. They differ from each other a lot in terms of phonetic realization of single vowels and diphthongs. Length is not straight-forwardly marked in standard orthography.

Stress is assigned to the initial syllable of a foot, with primary stress on the initial foot, secondary stress on all other feet. This just happens to align with morphological boundaries in some cases, such as some derivational and even some inflectional suffixes. A purely phonological (i.e., prosodic) rule is completely sufficient to describe the stress pattern.
The first syllable of the initial foot always receives primary stress (all other inital syllable of non-initial feet receive secondary stress).

In South Saami, the dual is not obligatory in the language of first language speakers (cf. also Bergsland 1946: 171). Usually, plural verb morphology is combined with dual personal pronouns: månnoeh vuejnebe (1DU see.1PL) 'we two see'. However, the dual is used in revitalized language/by second language speakers.

South Saami uses differential object marking (DOM) to express definiteness of objects in the plural. Plural objects marked with the nominative have an indefinite reading, plural objects marked with the accusative have a definite reading.

Situational necessity is expressed by two auxiliaries (which have the same etymology) and the infinitive of the main verb. Objective necessity is denoted by mås-, while moral obligation is expressed by mustə-.
Epistemic possibility is expressed by modal adverbs, for ex. əťə pə ’certainly’.
Deontic possibility is expressed by constructions which entail a present participle and a modal meaning word kim ’possibility’.
Particle ʌüwə ’let’ + indicative.

Such usages could be regarded as instances of Russian influence.
No copula is needed, e.g. păɣ-am jəm aj-qo;son-1SG (good small_man) ‘My son is a nice young man'.
Standard negation is symmetric. Negative sentences only differ from affirmative sentences in a way that they entail the negative particle әntә.

A distinctive feature of Surgut Khanty consonantism is the presence of labialized velars (kw, ŋw, and most frequently ɣw) in environments where neighbouring Vakh dialects have plain velars preceded by rounded vowels, e.g. V jöŋ ‘ten’ =  Surg jeŋw, V öɣi ‘girl’ = Surg ä̌ɣwi, V lök ‘road’ = Surg lekw, V joɣən ‘river’ = Surg jăɣwən. However, in ortography there is no distinction, ɣo, ko and ŋo are often written using w, k and ŋ.
Only occurs in the middle or at the end of a word.
The number of the object is indexed on the verb, e.g. 1SG meə-w° (singular object), 1SG meŋa-xəyu-n° (dual object), 1SG me-yə-n° (plural object); me- ‘to take, to do’.
Still, number concord is more common.
In different-subject sentences, the lexical dependent subject is marked with the genitive.
The object of transitive verbs is marked with the accusative both in finite as well as non-finite clauses.
Objects are typically marked with the accusative case. However, in the imperative also the nominative case is possible.
There are the frequentatie-iterative-multiplicative suffixes -or, -ur, -er indicating that a situation is repeated, habitual or dispersive.
The future tense conveys both immediate as well as remote future.

Whereas imperfective verbs typically have progressive reading, the perfective verbs usually indicate remote past. In addition, a perfective verb may be used to denote an event, which occurred before another event in the past.
Aspectual morphology is expressed on the lexical verb.
The inferential evidential is also used in the mirative or exclamative function.
The horative is used to express exhortations to the first person; it appears in 1SG, 1DU and 1PL.
The reflexive conjugation is formed based on the reflexive stem.
There is the purposive converb (final gerund).
The subject (god/sky/wheather) can be omitted although it is more common to express the subject.
The copula is not needed for the past tense, but it is needed for the future tense.
Coordinating conjunctions can be found but this is not the commonest coordination strategy.
There are two existential copulas: tənʹa° (affirmative) and yəŋku (negative). Cf. standard negation: pida nʹī məncara-q (he NEG work-CONNEG) 'He did not work / he is not working'.
Modal, purposive, and conditional coverbs can be negated like finite verbs.
For instance, n'iwa negates action nominals.
Only transitive verbs are passivized.
When agreeing with the head noun, participles can take possessive suffixes.
"In same-subject sentences the dependent subject stands in the nominative form if it is overt and triggers person/number marker of the possessive type" (Nikolaeva 2014: 286).
See UT060.
There is no special agentive nominalization form, present participles are used regularly as agentive nominalizations.
The diminutive marking on verbs expresses the meaning 'for some time, for a while'.
There is no synthetic superlative. Superlatives are formed with the help of adverbs expressing 'very', 'most', e.g. s'am'anəxət° 'most'.
Pronominal object can be marked in the postposition.
Local postpositions usually appear in the locative (n´ana 'at'), dative (nʹah  'to'), (ablative nʹad° 'from') and prolative form (nʹamna 'along').

With numerals the quantified noun can stand in the singular or plural. In Tereshchenko (1965), it is usually in the singular. However, the speakers of the modern language prefer the plural, though may accept
the singular as well.
The dative case also expresses lative meanings.
There is a caritive adverbial form that ends in -s'iq.
The dative case (-n°h ~ -t°h) is used; it is regarded as a local case.
There is the locative case, which additionally expresses instrumental and comitative meanings, means of transportation as well as cause.
The Locative case may be used in both functions.
The derivational suffix -ngæ appears in a similar function, e.g. li 'bone', lingæ 'as a bone, for a bone'.
However, there is an adverbial form marked by the suffix -(də)r'em.
The predistinative is used.
Paired objects typically stand in plural, still, dual may be encountered as well - 'my eyes’ can be expressed either as sǣw°-xəyu-nʹi (DU) or as sǣw°-nʹi (PL).
Whereas the lexical possessor takes the genitive form, the pronominal possessor appears in the nominative form.

"[T]he 3rd person singular possessive affixes express identifiability based on deixis and situational context" (Nikolaeva 2014: 68). Their usage in this function is, however, optional.

In literary language there are some loanwords beginning with r but there are no inherited stems beginning with r. In Russian loans beginning with r-, xa- or ng- may be pronounced in some dialects (e.g. risuida-> xarisuida- (< рисовать), ngrajonnoj (< районный). In older loanwords r- may be replaced by l-.

The analytic formation is, however, more common, e.g. Ana hiän tulou huomena (give.IMP.2G 3SG come.3SG tomorrow) 'Let him/her come tomorrow'.
Nowadays it is common to drop the copula, which can be regarded as Russian influence, e.g. Miun muamo (on) opaštaja (1SG-GEN mother (be.3SG) teacher) 'My mother is a teacher'.
